If any one is still out there.....<br><br>
Dr. Barry Spatz,<br>
Granted Nurse Ratchet maybe rapped your knuckles a bit, but it was done in a candid, civilized way.  Your reply was one of the most eggregious flames I've ever seen, and beyond the bounds of propriety.  The whole world does not need to know how pissed off you are capable of getting.  If you can't stand the heat......  Unless you've been totally wrapped up in your own hurt; you would have seen in these pages that there are people carrying all sorts of non-physical wounds from the Vietnam, and very likely some hurt worse than you do.  Your very vehemence made Nurse Ratchet's original point.<br><br>
To Jeffrey,<br>
Please be more careful of your history.  Stalin killed over 10 million in the &quot;collectivization&quot; and power consolidation <br>
purges of the mid-'30s before Hitler ever got started. Even during the life and death struggle with Germany during WWII, people were purged out of the Army regularly, and Stalin had 30 years to build up a total.  The Katyn Forest massacre in eastern Poland, for instance, was a Russian atrocity, not a German one.  This does not excuse the Holocaust by any means.  Given enough time in power, I believe Hitler would have eventually exceeded Stalin's totals, unless you are laying the all WWII casualties at his door step, which would put him higher; though I think the Japanese get some responsibility here.  When you add the deaths in China, Vietnam, Cambodia, Laos and Korea since 1945 in, Communism<br>
passes up Fascism by quite a bit.  10 million for the cultural revolution in China alone.<br><br>
Also please don't overestimate the ignorance of the avarage American on Communism, at least as of 30 to 40 years ago.  When I was growing up in the 50's, too many Americans saw Communists under the beds, but they were scared precisely they had no illusions of what Communism would do.  Priests and ministers were regularly imprisoned and executed in Eastern Europe before Stalin died.  The same Mexican government that provided assylum to Trotsky also executed some Catholic priests.  When a group of WWII vets, including my father, battled Communists for control of the CIO (before it's merger with the AFL) in the late '40s; the local Communists tried to intimidate our family by shadowing our home.<br>

